ARTICLE VII MANAGEMENT
7.1. Manager. The Company shall be managed by a Manager, as described herein. The Manager of the Company shall manage the Company in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement. Except as otherwise expressly set forth in this Agreement, the Manager shall be responsible for conducting the daily business affairs of the Company and for making decisions of the Company. The initial Manager of the Company is FR2. The Manager and Common Facilities Manager shall cooperate in good faith with each other so that the Common Facilities Manager and the Manager can perform their obligations under the Common Facilities Agreement and this Agreement, respectively, and the Members, Manager and Common Facilities Manager shall cooperate in good faith with respect to providing any written clarifications requested by either the Manager or the Common Facilities Manager in connection with such obligations. The Members shall cause Common Facilities Manager to comply with the foregoing sentence. Without limiting the foregoing, subject to Section 7.2, Section 7.3 and Section 7.8, the Manager shall have the power, without further consent or approval of the Members:
(a) To employ from time to time, at the expense of the Members, persons, firms or corporations to render services generally needed to accomplish the purposes of the Company with respect to the Shared GIA;
(b) To pay and collect funds to pay Shared GIA Expenses in accordance with this Agreement;
(c) To promptly provide any notices received by the Company to the Members with respect to the Shared GIA; and
(d) To execute, acknowledge, and deliver on behalf of the Company any and all documents and take such other steps as are reasonably necessary to effectuate the foregoing and as are consistent therewith.
7.2. Limitations on Authority. Notwithstanding anything in this Agreement to the contrary, the Manager shall not be permitted to do or take any of the following actions without the express prior written consent of the other Members:
(a) Disposition of Assets. Selling, leasing, pledging, mortgaging, conveying, licensing, exchanging or otherwise transferring or disposing of the Shared GIA, or amending, modifying, terminating or supplementing the Shared GIA;
(b) Borrowing. Borrowing any money on behalf of or in the name of the Company, utilizing the Company???s property as security for any loans, obligating the Company as guarantor, endorser, surety or accommodation party, or otherwise pledging the credit of the Company in any way other than the incurring of trade accounts in the ordinary course of business
(provided, however, nothing in this clause shall be deemed to prevent or prohibit any Member from borrowing funds, issuing guarantees, or encumbering its assets, including its Membership Interests, in connection with any corporate financing or any project financing of such Member???s Project);
(c) Loans. Lending any money, or extending any credit, on behalf of or in the name of the Company;
(d) Affiliate Contracts. Causing the Company to enter into agreements with Affiliates of the Manager;
(e) New Business. Commencing or participating in any new business activities other than the ownership, administration and management of the Shared GIA;
(f) Bankruptcy. Causing the Company to take or file any action or institute any proceedings in bankruptcy or insolvency;
(g) Mergers. Causing any merger, joint venture, or consolidation or other business combination of or involving the Company; and
(h) Additional Membership Interests. Issuing or redeeming of any Membership Interests or other equity interest of any kind in the Company, or any warrants, rights or options to acquire the same, or any security convertible into any of the foregoing.
(i) Contracts. Executing, amending, modifying, terminating or supplementing the Shared GIA or any other agreement on behalf of or in the name of the Company;
(j) Expenditures. Making any expenditure on behalf of the Company for any equipment, materials, assets or other items or services, or making any capital or other non- recurring expenditure, or consenting or agreeing to do any of the foregoing, unless otherwise contemplated in the Shared GIA or permitted under Section 7.3, provided, however, that the Manager may make reasonable expenditures in excess of what is permitted under Section 7.3 to respond to an emergency and/or to comply with applicable Laws;
(k) Lawsuits and Settlements. Settling, compromising, assigning, pledging, transferring, releasing or consenting to do the same, any claim, suit, debt, demand or judgment against, or due or by the Company or the Manager on behalf of the Company, submitting any such claim, dispute or controversy to arbitration or judicial process, or stipulation thereof to a judgment, or consent to do the same to the extent that any of the foregoing relate to an amount in controversy in excess of $100,000 (or, if a greater amount, the amount covered by applicable insurance proceeds); or
(l) Governing Authority. Taking any action contradictory to an express directive or instruction given by the Company, so long as such directive or instruction does not violate any Laws or the Shared GIA.
7.3. Company Expenses.
(a) General. The Manager shall provide to the Members written notice of any and all amounts due and owing by the Company at least thirty (30) days prior to the due date for such amounts. Except for the Shared GIA Expenses, which are covered exclusively in Section 4.2(e), the Manager shall be responsible for paying any and all amounts due and owing by the Company (collectively, the ???Non-Shared GIA Expenses???) on or prior to the due date for such Non- Shared GIA Expenses; provided, however, that in no event shall the Manager be permitted to allow the Company to incur any Non-Shared GIA Expenses or other payment obligations (other than the Shared GIA Expenses) in excess of $20,000 individually, or $50,000 in the aggregate in any calendar year, without the prior written consent of both Members.
(b) Reimbursement. Each Member shall pay and reimburse the Manager in proportion to its Shared GIA Ratio for all Non-Shared GIA Expenses paid by the Manager in accordance with Section 7.3(a) within thirty (30) days after such payment by Manager thereof. If any Member fails to timely make any required payment of amounts due under this Section 7.3(b) and such failure continues for five (5) Business Days after such Member receives notice of such failure, then such amount shall begin to accrue interest from the date of such notice until paid at the Default Rate. Such remedy shall be in addition to the right of the Manager and other Member to pursue any other remedies that may be available to it under applicable law or this Agreement.
7.4. Members Separate. Except as expressly set forth herein, no Member, in its capacity as such, shall have any right, power or authority to take part in the management or control of the business of the Company.
7.5. Reliance by Third Parties. Any Person dealing with the Company, other than a Member, may rely on the authority of the Manager in taking any action that is in the name of the Company without inquiry into the provisions of this Agreement or compliance therewith. Except for Section 4.2(d), no representative of a Member acting solely in his or her capacity as such shall have any authority to bind the Company to any third party with respect to any action.
7.6. Delegation of Authority.
(a) The Manager may, from time to time, delegate to one or more officers of the Company such authority and duties as the Manager may deem advisable to carry out the day- to-day business of the Company, whether on a Project basis or otherwise, but such delegation shall not relieve the Manager of its obligations under this Agreement. In addition, the Manager may, from time to time assign titles (including, president, vice president, secretary and treasurer) to any such officers selected by the Manager. Unless the Manager decides otherwise or except as otherwise provided in this Agreement, if the title is one commonly used for officers of a business corporation, the assignment of such title shall constitute the delegation of the authority and duties that are normally associated with that office, subject to any specific delegation of authority and duties or any limitation or restriction on authority pursuant to this Section 7.6. Unless otherwise provided by Law, any number of titles may be held by the same individual. The initial president of the Company shall be appointed by the Manager.
(b) The Manager may, from time to time, delegate its authority and duties as the Manager to any other Person as the Manager may deem advisable (such Person, the ???Delegate???), but such delegation shall not relieve the Manager of its obligations under this
Agreement. In addition, the Manager may assign to the Delegate its rights to compensation and reimbursement as set forth in Sections 4.2(e) and 7.13.
(c) Any delegation pursuant to this Section 7.6 may be revoked at any time by the Manager.
7.7. Prudent Management. The Manager covenants and agrees to manage, administer, supervise, operate, and maintain the Company and the Shared GIA in accordance with this Agreement, Prudent Wind Industry Practices and good faith and fair dealing and, except as expressly required by this Agreement, the Manager shall not discriminate against any Member???s Project in connection therewith.
7.8. Affiliate Contracts. Any agreement entered into by the Company or that otherwise results in Shared Expenses, in each case, and entered into with an Affiliate of any Member shall contain fees charged based on fair market value and be no less favorable than an agreement that could be obtained in a comparable arms??? length transaction with an equally experienced Person not an Affiliate of a Member. The Manager and the service provider shall provide a certificate to that effect.
7.9. Indemnification of Manager. The Members shall defend, indemnify and hold harmless, each in proportion to its Shared GIA Ratio, the Manager, and its employees and agents, from any claim, loss, liability or damage incurred by reason of an act performed or omitted to be performed by it in good faith in the discharge of its duties hereunder as the Manager or in the exercise of its powers and authority hereunder as the Manager, whether or not as a result of the Manager???s (or its employees??? or agents???) negligent acts or omissions, other than acts or omissions constituting fraud, willful misconduct, or gross negligence, including reasonable attorneys??? fees incurred by it in connection with the defense of any action based on any such alleged act or omission. The Delegate shall be a third party beneficiary of this Section 7.9.
7.10. Manager Limitation of Liability. In the exercise of its duties hereunder, the Manager shall exercise such care, skill and diligence as a business entity engaged in the management of wind energy projects would normally exercise. The Manager and its employees and agents shall not be liable, responsible or accountable for any claim, loss, liability or damage incurred by reason of an act performed or omitted to be performed by it in good faith in the discharge of its duties hereunder as the Manager or in the exercise of its powers and authority hereunder as the Manager, whether or not as a result of the Manager???s (or its employees??? or agents???) negligent acts or omissions, other than acts or omissions constituting fraud, willful misconduct or gross negligence.
7.11. Removal of Manager. The Manager may be removed (a) if (i) an insolvency proceeding has been commenced against the Manager and such proceeding continues undismissed for sixty (60) days or (ii) the Manager institutes an insolvency proceeding with respect to itself, or admits in writing its inability to pay its indebtedness generally as it becomes due or fails generally to pay its indebtedness as it becomes due, or any action is taken by the Manager for the purpose of effecting any of the foregoing or any analogous proceeding or (b) for cause by any Member; provided that, only in the event of removal under this clause (b), each of the following conditions are satisfied: (i) the Manager has defaulted in its material obligations under this Agreement; (ii)
the Member seeking removal of the Manager for cause has provided written notice to the Manager and the other Members of such default by the Manager hereunder, which notice shall contain a general description of the facts and circumstances giving rise to such default; and (iii) the Manager has failed to cure such default described in the notice within thirty (30) days after delivery of such written notice; provided that, if such default is not reasonably capable of being cured within thirty (30) days, then the Manager shall have an additional period of time, but in no event more than ninety (90) days from the delivery of such written notice to cure such default. No removal of the Manager shall be effective unless and until a successor Manager is appointed by the Members (such successor however may not be the Member that has been acting as the removed Manager).
7.12. Step-in Rights. If the Manager defaults in its material obligations under this Agreement or fails to perform any of its material obligations under this Agreement, in each case, after the receipt of a written notice from a Member identifying such breach or non-performance and the expiration of a thirty (30)-day cure period (which cure period may be extended for up to ninety (90) days if the breach or non-performance cannot reasonably be cured within such thirty (30)-day period and the Manager is otherwise exercising commercially reasonable efforts to effectuate a cure or remedy such non-performance), then such Member shall have the right to step- in and effectuate such cure or perform on behalf of the Manager after the expiration of the relevant cure period.
7.13. Fixed Fee.
(a) As consideration for the services to be performed by the Manager hereunder, beginning on the date hereof, the Company shall pay the Manager an annual fee (as adjusted pursuant to Section 7.13(b), the ???Fixed Fee???) equal to Five Thousand Dollars ($5,000.00). The Fixed Fee for the first year of the term hereof shall be payable on the Effective Date, and the Fixed Fee shall thereafter be paid annually on each subsequent anniversary thereof and may be prorated for a partial year at the beginning and end of the Manager???s tenure as the Manager hereunder in accordance with Section 4.2(e).
(b) The Fixed Fee shall be increased (but not decreased) annually for each calendar year, beginning January 1 of the first year after the date of this Agreement by a factor of one hundred percent (100%) of the percentage change in the GDPIPD, during such preceding calendar year.
ARTICLE VIII TAX ALLOCATIONS
8.1. Allocations of Net Profits and Net Losses. Net Profits and Net Losses for any Fiscal Year shall be allocated among the Members in such manner that, as of the end of such Fiscal Year, the sum of (a) the Capital Account of each Member, (b) such Member???s share of minimum gain (as determined according to U.S. Treasury Regulations section 1.704-2(g)) and (c) such Member???s Member Nonrecourse Debt Minimum Gain shall be equal to the respective net amounts which would be distributed to such Member under this Agreement, determined as if the Company were to (a) liquidate all of the assets of the Company for an amount equal to their Gross Asset Values and (b) distribute the proceeds in liquidation pursuant to Section 12.3.
8.2. Special Allocations. The following special allocations shall be made in the following order:
(a) Minimum Gain Chargeback. Except as otherwise provided in U.S. Treasury Regulations Section 1.704-2(f), notwithstanding any other provision of this Article VIII, if there is a net decrease in Company Minimum Gain during any Fiscal Year, each Member shall be specially allocated items of Company income and gain for such Fiscal Year (and, if necessary, subsequent Fiscal Years) in an amount equal to such Member???s share of the net decrease in Company Minimum Gain, determined in accordance with U.S. Treasury Regulations section 1.704-2(g). Allocations pursuant to the previous sentence shall be made in proportion to the respective amounts required to be allocated to each Member pursuant thereto. The items to be so allocated shall be determined in accordance with U.S. Treasury Regulations sections 1.704-2(f)(6) and 1.704-2(j)(2). This Section 8.2(a) is intended to comply with the minimum gain chargeback requirement in U.S. Treasury Regulations section 1.704-2(f) and shall be interpreted consistently therewith.
(b) Member Minimum Gain Chargeback. Except as otherwise provided in U.S. Treasury Regulations section 1.704-2(i)(4), notwithstanding any other provision of this Article VIII, if there is a net decrease in Member Nonrecourse Debt Minimum Gain attributable to a Member Nonrecourse Debt during any Fiscal Year, each Member who has a share of the Member Nonrecourse Debt Minimum Gain attributable to such Member Nonrecourse Debt, determined in accordance with U.S. Treasury Regulations section 1.704-2(i)(5), shall be specially allocated items of Company income and gain for such Fiscal Year (and, if necessary, subsequent Fiscal Years) in an amount equal to such Member???s share of the net decrease in Member Nonrecourse Debt, determined in accordance with U.S. Treasury Regulations section 1.704-2(i)(4). Allocations pursuant to the previous sentence shall be made in proportion to the respective amounts required to be allocated to each Member pursuant thereto. The items to be so allocated shall be determined in accordance with U.S. Treasury Regulations sections 1.704-2(i)(4) and 1.704-2(j)(2). This Section 8.2(b) is intended to comply with the minimum gain chargeback requirement in U.S. Treasury Regulations section 1.704-2(i)(4) and shall be interpreted consistently therewith.
(c) Qualified Income Offset. In the event any Member unexpectedly receives any adjustments, allocations, or distributions described in U.S. Treasury Regulations sections 1.704-1(b)(2)(ii)(d)(4), 1.704-1(b)(2)(ii)(d)(5), or 1.704-1(b)(2)(ii)(d)(6), items of Company income and gain shall be specially allocated to such Member in an amount and manner sufficient to eliminate, to the extent required by the U.S. Treasury Regulations, the Adjusted Capital Account Deficit of the Member as quickly as possible, provided that an allocation pursuant to this Section 8.2(c) shall be made only if and to the extent that the Member would have an Adjusted Capital Account Deficit after all other allocations provided for in this Article VIII have been tentatively made as if this Section 8.2(c) were not in the Agreement.
(d) Gross Income Allocation. In the event any Member has a deficit Capital Account at the end of any Fiscal Year that is in excess of the sum of (i) the amount such Member is obligated to restore pursuant to the penultimate sentences of U.S. Treasury Regulations sections 1.704-2(g)(1) and 1.704-2(i)(5), each such Member shall be specially allocated items of Company income and gain in the amount of such excess as quickly as possible; provided that an allocation pursuant to this Section 8.2(d) shall be made only if and to the extent that such Member would
have a deficit Capital Account in excess of such sum after all other allocations provided for in this Article VIII have been made as if Section 8.2(c) and this Section 8.2(d) were not in the Agreement.
(e) Nonrecourse Deductions. Nonrecourse Deductions for any Fiscal Year shall be specially allocated to the Members in proportion to their respective percentage interests.
(f) Member Nonrecourse Deductions. Any Member Nonrecourse Deductions for any Fiscal Year shall be specially allocated to the Member who bears the economic risk of loss with respect to the Member Nonrecourse Debt to which such Member Nonrecourse Deductions are attributable in accordance with U.S. Treasury Regulations section 1.704-2(i)(1).
(g) Section 754 Adjustments. To the extent an adjustment to the adjusted U.S. federal income tax basis of any Company asset, pursuant to Code sections 734(b) or 743(b) is required, pursuant to U.S. Treasury Regulations sections 1.704-1(b)(2)(iv)(m)(2) or 1.704- 1(b)(2)(iv)(m)(4), to be taken into account in determining Capital Accounts as the result of a distribution to a Member in complete liquidation of such Member???s interest in the Company, the amount of such adjustment to Capital Accounts shall be treated as an item of gain (if the adjustment increases the U.S. federal income tax basis of the asset) or loss (if the adjustment decreases such basis) and such gain or loss shall be specially allocated to the Members in accordance with their interests in the Company in the event U.S. Treasury Regulations section 1.704-1(b)(2)(iv)(m)(2) applies, or to the Member to whom such distribution was made in the event U.S. Treasury Regulations section 1.704-1(b)(2)(iv)(m)(4) applies.
8.3. Curative Allocations. The allocations set forth in Sections 8.2(a), 8.2(b), 8.2(c), 8.2(d), 8.2(e), 8.2(f), 8.2(g), and 8.4 (the ???Regulatory Allocations???) are intended to comply with certain requirements of the U.S. Treasury Regulations. It is the intent of the Members that, to the extent possible, all Regulatory Allocations shall be offset either with other Regulatory Allocations or with special allocations of other items of Company income, gain, loss, or deduction pursuant to this Section 8.3. Therefore, notwithstanding any other provision of Article VIII (other than the Regulatory Allocations), the Manager shall make such offsetting special allocations of Company income, gain, loss, or deduction in whatever manner it determines appropriate so that, after such offsetting allocations are made, each Member???s Capital Account balance is, to the extent possible, equal to the Capital Account balance such Member would have had if the Regulatory Allocations were not part of the Agreement and all Company items were allocated pursuant to Section 8.1. In exercising its discretion under this Section 8.3, the Manager shall take into account future Regulatory Allocations under Sections 8.2(a) and 8.2(b) that, although not yet made, are likely to offset other Regulatory Allocations previously made under Sections 8.2(e) and 8.2(f).
8.4. Loss Limitation. Losses allocated pursuant to Section 8.1 hereof shall not exceed the maximum amount of losses that can be allocated without causing any Member to have an Adjusted Capital Account Deficit at the end of any Fiscal Year. In the event some but not all of the Members would have Adjusted Capital Account Deficits as a consequence of an allocation of losses pursuant to Section 8.1 hereof, the limitation set forth in this Section 8.4 shall be applied on a Member by Member basis and losses not allocable to any Member as a result of such limitation shall be allocated to the other Members in accordance with the positive balances in such Member???s Capital Accounts so as to allocate the maximum permissible losses to each Member under U.S. Treasury Regulations section 1.704-1(b)(2)(ii)(d).
8.5. Tax Allocations; Section 704(c) of the Code. Except as otherwise provided in this Section 8.5, each item of income, gain, loss and deduction of the Company for U.S. federal income tax purposes shall be allocated among the Members in the same manner as such items are allocated for book purposes under this Article VIII. In accordance with Code section 704(c) and the U.S. Treasury Regulations thereunder, income, gain, loss, and deduction with respect to any property contributed to the capital of the Company shall, solely for tax purposes, be allocated among the Members so as to take account of any variation between the adjusted U.S. federal income tax basis of such property to the Company for U.S. federal income tax purposes and its initial Gross Asset Value (computed in accordance with the definition of Gross Asset Value) using any method permitted pursuant to the U.S. Treasury Regulations under Code section 704(c) that is chosen by the Manager. In the event the Gross Asset Value of any Company asset is adjusted pursuant to subparagraph (ii) of the definition of Gross Asset Value, subsequent allocations of income, gain, loss, and deduction with respect to such asset shall take account of any variation between the adjusted basis of such asset for federal income tax purposes and its Gross Asset Value in the same manner as under Code section 704(c) and the U.S. Treasury Regulations thereunder.
ARTICLE IX DISTRIBUTIONS
9.1. Distributions. At least annually, the Manager will cause the Company to distribute to the Members any cash flow of the Company in excess of anticipated expenses in proportion to each Member???s Shared GIA Ratio during such Fiscal Year. If the Member???s Shared GIA Ratios vary during a Fiscal Year, such allocation will be determined by treating each portion of the Fiscal Year with different Shared GIA Ratios as a separate fiscal year.
ARTICLE X ACCOUNTING AND TAX MATTERS
10.1. Tax Returns. The Manager shall cause the preparation and timely filing of all tax returns required to be filed by the Company pursuant to the Code and all other tax returns deemed necessary and required in each jurisdiction in which the Company does business. The Manager shall provide each Member with Schedule K-I, Form 1065 (or any successor thereto) and analogous state and local tax forms by May 31 following the close of any Fiscal Year. In addition, it shall provide copies of any tax returns, or pertinent information therefrom, to the Members within a reasonable time after the end of the Company???s Fiscal Year upon the Members??? written request. In any event and at the request of any Member that has transferred its interest or any portion thereof, the Manager shall make the election provided for in Code section 754.
10.2. Capital Accounts. A separate Capital Account will be maintained for each Member as set forth below:
(a) The Capital Account of a Member shall mean the capital account of that Member determined from the inception of the Company strictly in accordance with the rules set forth in Section 1.704-1(b)(2)(iv) of the Treasury Regulations. Subject to the previous sentence, the ???Capital Account??? shall mean: (i) the amount of money contributed by the Member to the Company; and (ii) the fair market value of property contributed by the Member to the Company (net of liabilities secured by the property or to which the property is subject); increased by (iii) the
amount of Net Profits allocated to the Member and any items in the nature of income or gain that are specially allocated pursuant to Section 8.2 or Section 8.3; and decreased by (iv) the amount of money distributed to the Member; (v) the fair market value of property distributed to the Member by the Company (net of liabilities secured by the property or to which the property is subject); and (vi) the amount of Net Losses allocated to the Member and any items in the nature of expenses or losses that are specially allocated pursuant to Section 8.2 or Section 8.3.
(b) In determining Capital Accounts, an assumption of a Member???s unsecured liability by the Company shall be treated as a distribution of cash to the Member. An assumption of the Company???s unsecured liability by a Member shall be treated as a cash contribution to the Company. For this purpose, the assumption of a secured liability in excess of the fair market value of the security shall be treated as the assumption of an unsecured liability to the extent of that excess.
(c) In the event that assets of the Company other than cash are distributed to a Member in kind, Capital Accounts shall be adjusted for the hypothetical gain or loss that would have been realized by the Company if the distributed assets had been sold for their fair market values in a cash sale (in order to reflect unrealized gain or loss).
(d) In the case of a transfer of Membership Interests, the transferee shall inherit the Capital Account of the transferor with respect to such Membership Interests, subject to any permitted adjustments under the Treasury Regulations.
(e) In the event of the acquisition of any additional Membership Interests by any new or existing Member in exchange for more than a de minimis Capital Contribution, the assets of the Company shall be revalued and the Members??? Capital Accounts adjusted to reflect the gain (or loss) that would have been allocated to each Member if all the assets of the Company had been sold at their fair market value immediately prior to the acquisition of the additional Membership Interests.
(f) Except as otherwise required by the Delaware Act, no Member shall have any liability to restore all or any portion of a deficit in such Member???s Capital Account.
10.3. Accounting Period. The Company???s ???Fiscal Year??? shall be the calendar year.
10.4. Books and Records. Proper and complete records and books of account shall be kept or shall be caused to be kept by the Company in which shall be entered fully and accurately all transactions relating to the Company???s business in such detail and completeness as is customary and usual for businesses of the type engaged in by the Company. The books and records shall at all times be maintained at the principal place of business of the Company. A Member or a permitted assignee of either Member???s Membership Interests, on written request, may examine and copy, in person or by such Member???s or assignee???s representative, at any reasonable time, for any proper purpose, and at the Member???s expense, records and books of the Company and such other information regarding the business, affairs, and financial condition of the Company as is just and reasonable.
10.5. Partnership Representative. The Manager is hereby designated as the partnership representative of the Company, as provided in Code Section 6223 (the ???Partnership Representative???), unless and until removed and replaced by the Members, and as such shall perform the duties as are required or appropriate thereunder. Each Member by the execution of this Agreement consents to such designation of the Partnership Representative and agrees to execute, certify, acknowledge, deliver, swear to, file and record at the appropriate public offices such documents as may be necessary or appropriate to evidence such consent. Legal and accounting fees and costs incurred in connection with the exercise of the duties of the Partnership Representative shall be paid directly by the Company and treated as Shared GIA Expenses. The Partnership Representative shall consult with and keep all the Members fully and promptly informed of all matters arising in connection with such duties, including without limitation promptly providing the Members with copies of all relevant documentation and correspondence. The Partnership Representative shall not settle any dispute or agree to extend the statute of limitations without the consent of all other Members, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld.
10.6 Partnership Adjustments. If the Company receives a notice of final partnership adjustment as described in Section 6226 of the Code, the Company shall elect pursuant to Section 6226 of the Code, and follow the procedures required in connection with such election, to make inapplicable to the Company the requirement in Section 6225 of the Code that the Company pay the ???imputed underpayment??? as that term is used in Section 6225 of the Code.
ARTICLE XI TRANSFERABILITY
11.1. General Restriction. No Member may Transfer its Membership Interests without the consent of the other Members; provided, however, no consent of the other Members shall be required (i) in connection with the Transfer of its Membership Interests when made together with a Transfer of all or substantially all of its respective Project Controlled Assets (ii) as collateral to a Lender of the assignor, (iii) in connection with a foreclosure (or any transfer in lieu of foreclosure) by a Lender; provided that in each case, the new owner shall be assigned and shall assume the Transferring Member???s interest in this Agreement to the extent of the interest Transferred as a condition to the assignment, in whole or in part, according to whether the Transfer was total or partial, and the new owner shall execute a joinder in accordance with Section 5.4.
11.2. FERC or other Governmental Approvals. Notwithstanding anything in this Article XI to the contrary, no Transfer of any Membership Interests shall be effective unless and until the Company has obtained any necessary approvals from FERC as may be required under the Federal Power Act or from any Delaware state regulatory agency having jurisdiction over the Company or the Shared GIA and such Transfer complies with the Securities Act, the Exchange Act, the Investment Company Act, or the laws, rules, regulations, orders and other directives of any Governmental Authority.
11.3. Lender Protections.
(a) Each Member (i) acknowledges that each other Member may enter into financing documents with one or more Lenders evidencing, securing or otherwise relating to Phase
Financing and (ii) consents to the pledge and collateral assignment under such financing documents of all of such Member???s Membership Interests and rights and obligations under this Agreement to secure such Phase Financing, subject to the terms contained herein. As a precondition to exercising any remedies related to any alleged default by a Member under this Agreement, the other Member, as required hereunder, shall give notice of default giving rise to such right to exercise such remedies to each Lender that has provided Phase Financing to such Member at the same time it delivers such notice of default to the first Member, specifying in detail the alleged event of default and the required remedy. Each such Lender shall have the same amount of time to cure the default as is given to the first Member and the same right to cure any default as the first Member. The cure period for each Lender shall begin to run at the end of the cure period given to Members in this Agreement, but in no case shall the cure period for any Lender be less than thirty (30) days after receipt of the notice of default. The Lender to such defaulting Member shall have the absolute right to substitute itself for the defaulting Member and perform the duties of the first Member hereunder for purposes of curing such event of default. Each Member expressly consents to such substitution, agrees to accept such performance.
(b) Any Lender that does not directly hold any Membership Interests, or whose Membership Interests are held solely for security purposes, shall have no obligation or liability to any other Member for performance of a Member???s obligations under this Agreement prior to the time such Lender directly holds any Membership Interests, or succeeds to absolute title to a Member???s Membership Interests. A Lender (or its designee) shall be liable to perform obligations of a Member to another Member under this Agreement only to the extent such Lender or its designee has acquired the Membership Interests at foreclosure, by transfer in lieu of foreclosure or by other lawful means and has elected to be bound hereby. Further, in the event that a Lender or its assignee elects to (i) perform a Member???s obligations under this Agreement, (ii) acquire any portion of a Member???s right, title or interest in all or any of the Membership Interests or (iii) enter into a new agreement as provided in Section 11.3(f), then such Lender shall not have any personal liability to any of the Members in connection therewith. Moreover, any Lender or other Person who acquires Membership Interests pursuant to foreclosure or an assignment in lieu of foreclosure shall not be liable to perform any obligations under this Agreement to the extent the same are incurred or accrue after such Lender or other Person no longer has ownership of such interest.
(c) A Lender shall have the absolute right: (i) to assign its lien; (ii) to enforce its lien and acquire or cause the sale or other transfer of the applicable Membership Interests at foreclosure by transfer in lieu of foreclosure or any other lawful means; and (iii) to perform all obligations to be performed by a Member under this Agreement, or to cause a receiver to be appointed to do so. No Member???s consent shall be required for any of the foregoing, and upon acquisition of Membership Interests by a Lender or its designee or any other third party who acquires the same at foreclosure or by transfer in lieu of foreclosure, a Member shall recognize the Lender or such other party (as the case may be) as the other Member???s proper successor, and this Agreement shall remain in full force and effect.
(d) Following acquisition of a Membership Interests by the Lender or its designee as a result of either foreclosure or acceptance of an assignment in lieu of foreclosure, or by a purchaser at a foreclosure sale, this Agreement shall continue in full force and effect and the Lender or party acquiring title to such Membership Interests shall, as promptly as reasonably possible, commence the cure of all defaults under this Agreement and thereafter diligently pursue
such cure to completion; provided, however, that the Lender or party acquiring title to such interest in the Shared Assets shall not be required to cure those defaults which are not reasonably susceptible of being cured or performed (???Non-Curable Defaults???). Non-Curable Defaults shall be deemed waived by a Member upon completion of foreclosure proceedings or acquisition of the defaulting Member???s interest in the Membership Interests by such party. If a Lender is prohibited by any process or injunction issued by any court or by reason of any action of any court having jurisdiction over any bankruptcy or insolvency proceeding involving the defaulting Member from commencing or prosecuting the appropriate judicial or non-judicial proceedings, then any cure period for commencing such proceedings shall be extended for the period of such prohibition; provided, in no event shall such cure period extend beyond one hundred eighty (180) days.
(e) Neither the bankruptcy nor the insolvency of a Member shall be grounds for terminating this Agreement as long as all payments and all other monetary charges payable by the Member under this Agreement are paid by the Lender in accordance with the terms of this Agreement.
(f) In the event that this Agreement is rejected or disaffirmed pursuant to bankruptcy law or any other law affecting creditors??? rights, then, so long as a Lender has cured any such event of default other than Non-Curable Defaults, the non-defaulting Members shall, immediately upon request from such Lender received within ninety (90) days after any such event, without demanding additional consideration therefor, enter into a limited liability company agreement with such Lender, which new limited liability company agreement shall contain the same covenants, agreements, terms, provisions and limitations as this Agreement (except for any requirements that have been fulfilled by the Members prior to such termination, foreclosure, rejection or disaffirmance). At the option of the Lender, the new limited liability company agreement may be executed by a designee of such Lender, with the Lender assuming the burdens and obligations of the defaulting Member thereunder. If more than one Lender makes a request for a new limited liability company agreement pursuant hereto, then the same shall be delivered to the Lender whose lien is senior in priority.
(g) Each Lender is a third party beneficiary of this Section 11.3.
11.4. No Other Liens.
(a) Except as expressly set forth in Section 11.3, (i) no Member shall, directly or indirectly, create, incur or cause to exist any lien on or encumbrance to be levied against or attached to the Membership Interests of any other Member, (ii) no Member shall create, incur or permit to exist any lien or encumbrance on its Membership Interests except for liens or encumbrances for taxes not yet delinquent or which are being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings, and (iii) no Member or Manager shall create, incur or cause to exist any lien on or encumbrance on the Shared GIA, in each case, including but not limited to any lien for unpaid taxes (except as provided in clause (ii) above), any judgment lien or any mechanic???s or materialmen???s lien. If any such lien or encumbrance attaches or a Member or the Manager receives notice of any such lien or encumbrance, the Member or Manager whose actual or alleged act or omission resulted in such lien or encumbrance shall cause such lien or encumbrance to be released and removed of record within fifteen (15) days of such attachment or notice, unless in the case of clause (ii) or (iii) above, (y) such Member or Manager (1) in good faith contests or disputes the
validity of such liens or encumbrances, (2) promptly commences legal action to remove such lien or encumbrance and (3) furnishes to the other Member or the Company a bond or other acceptable security in an amount sufficient to discharge all such contested liens and encumbrances and (z) during such period the lienholders??? proceedings are stayed. Each Member further agrees not to sell, lease, convey, transfer and/or assign, or to enter into any agreement with respect to the sale, lease, conveyance, transfer or assignment of the Shared GIA.
(b) Notwithstanding anything in Section 11.4(a) to the contrary, in accordance with Article XI, a Member may grant a lien on or security interest in its Membership Interests or such Member???s Project and any Member may obtain a judgment lien against any other Member based on any such other Member???s breach under this Agreement, or otherwise permitted at law or in equity, and not specifically prevented by this Agreement.
ARTICLE XII DISSOLUTION AND TERMINATION
12.1. Dissolution. The Company shall be dissolved upon the occurrence of any of the following events:
(a) A written agreement to dissolve is signed by all of the Members; or
(b) Upon the judicial dissolution of the Company pursuant to the applicable provisions of Delaware Act.
12.2. Effect of Dissolution. Upon an event of dissolution, the Company shall cease to carry on its business, except insofar as may be necessary for the winding up of its business, but its separate existence shall continue until the activities set forth in Section 12.3 have been completed. As soon as possible following the occurrence of any of the events specified in Section 12.1 effecting the dissolution of the Company, the Manager shall (a) execute a certificate of cancellation in such form as shall be prescribed by the Delaware Act and file the same with the Secretary of State, and (b) terminate all qualifications of the Company as a foreign limited liability company in all applicable jurisdictions.
12.3. Liquidation. Upon dissolution, an accounting shall be made of the accounts of the Company and of the Company???s assets, liabilities and operations, from the date of the last previous accounting until the date of dissolution. If the Company is dissolved and its affairs are to be wound up, the Manager shall discharge all liabilities of the Company, including liabilities to Members who are creditors to the extent otherwise permitted by law. Thereafter, all remaining assets of the Company shall be liquidated and, except as otherwise required by the Delaware Act, distributed to the Members in proportion to their positive Capital Accounts balances.
12.4. Deficit Capital Account Balance. Notwithstanding anything contained in this Agreement to the contrary, upon a liquidation, within the meaning of Section 1.704- 1(b)(2)(ii)(g) of the Treasury Regulations, if any Member has a deficit balance in the Member???s Capital Account (after giving effect to all contributions, distributions, allocations, and other Capital Account adjustments for all taxable years, including the year during which such liquidation occurs), the Member shall have no obligation to make any Capital Contribution to reduce or eliminate such deficit balance, and the deficit balance of the Member???s Capital Account shall not
be considered a debt owed by the Member to the Company or to any other Person for any purpose whatsoever. Upon any such liquidation, to the extent there is no deficit balance in the Member???s Capital Account, (after giving effect to all contributions, distributions, allocations, and other Capital Account adjustments for all taxable years, including the year during which such liquidation occurs), undivided interests in the assets of the Company shall be distributed in kind among the Members pro rata in accordance with their positive Capital Accounts balances, and the relationship of the Members shall be deemed to be a tenancy in common until such time as the Members terminate such relationship in writing.
12.5. Termination. The Company shall terminate when all affairs of the Company have been wound up and the certificate of cancellation contemplated by Section 12.2 has been properly filed with the Secretary of State.
12.6. Consequences of Termination. Upon the termination of the Company, all rights and obligations under this Agreement shall forthwith terminate; provided, however, that all claims of any Member against another Member for damages arising out of acts or omissions of such other Member in breach of this Agreement prior to such termination or outside the scope of this Agreement shall not be affected by termination of the Company.

14.12. Dispute Resolution Procedures.
(a) Applicability. Unless stated otherwise herein, all Disputes between the Members shall be resolved in accordance with the dispute resolution procedures set forth in this Section 14.12. Notwithstanding the foregoing, (a) the Members may at any time seek injunctive relief from a court of competent jurisdiction, and (b) nothing herein shall prevent a Member from defending or pursuing any claim in a court or other proceeding against a third party that has been initiated by such third party. In the event any Dispute involves common issues of fact, liability or responsibility with any dispute or controversy under this Agreement, the O&M Agreement or the Common Facilities Agreement, each of the Members agrees, where reasonably justified, to join such Dispute with such other disputes and controversies to seek a common resolution of all such matters.
(b) Negotiations by Senior Management.
(i) In the event of a Dispute, the Members will use all reasonable efforts to reach a satisfactory solution by referring the Dispute to senior management of each of the Members.
(ii) Senior management of the Members will meet as soon as possible, on no less than seven (7) days??? written notice, unless specifically agreed otherwise and shall negotiate in good faith. Senior management of the Members shall examine any submissions by the Members, and shall, if the Dispute cannot be resolved immediately, agree to convene for further negotiations aimed at resolving the Dispute.
(iii) Should senior management of the Members be unable to resolve the Dispute within thirty (30) days after commencement of negotiation by such senior management, either Member may, by delivery of written notice to the other, submit the Dispute to binding arbitration in accordance with Section 14.12(c).
(c) Binding Arbitration.
(i) If a Dispute remains unresolved after the discussions of senior management of the Members in accordance with Section 14.12(b) hereof, or if any Member fails to comply with any of the time periods set forth in Section 14.12(b) above, the Members agree that upon prior written notice to the other Member, either Member may submit such Dispute to binding arbitration and that all such Disputes shall be finally settled by binding arbitration, pursuant to the rules of the American Arbitration Association (the ???AAA???), by (subject to the first clause of Section 14.12(c)(ii)) three (3) arbitrators who are to be appointed in accordance with the said rules and who, to the extent possible, shall have experience and expertise in the subject matter involved in the Dispute.
(ii) Unless all Members can agree in writing on a single arbitrator within ten (10) days after the delivery of notice referred to in Section 14.12(b), then, within ten (10) days thereafter, each Member (which shall be entitled to specify one arbitrator), shall notify the other
Member in writing of the name of the independent arbitrator chosen by such Member to participate as a member of a three-member panel of arbitrators. If any Member fails to give the other timely notice of such appointment, then the Member who timely gave such notice shall be entitled to require that its arbitrator act as the sole arbitrator hereunder. If an arbitrator is timely appointed by each of the Members, the two named arbitrators shall select the third member of the arbitration panel within ten (10) days after they have both been appointed, and they shall promptly notify the Members thereof. Each Member shall promptly notify the other Member and the Member-selected arbitrators in writing if the third arbitrator has any relationship to or affiliation with such Member (a ???Notice of Relationship???), in which event another arbitrator shall be selected within ten (10) days after receipt of such Notice of Relationship by the Member-selected arbitrators. If the two initially appointed arbitrators cannot timely agree on a third arbitrator, then any Member may request that the AAA select the third arbitrator. The arbitrators, to the extent possible, shall have experience and expertise in the subject matter involved in the Dispute.
(iii) The arbitration hearing shall be held at a site in Houston, Texas, to be agreed to by a majority of the arbitrators on thirty (30) days??? written notice to the Members. The arbitration proceedings shall be held in the English language.
(iv) The arbitration hearing shall be concluded within one hundred twenty (120) days after it is commenced unless otherwise ordered by a majority of the arbitrators on compelling grounds, and the award thereon or decision with respect thereto shall be made within ten (10) days after the close of the submission of evidence; provided that failure by the arbitrators to conclude the arbitration hearing or make such award or decision within the foregoing deadlines shall not invalidate such arbitration hearing, award or decision. Arbitration demanded hereunder by any Member shall be final and binding on the Members. The decision, arbitration order and relief agreed upon in writing by any two or more of the arbitrators (in the case of a three-member panel) shall be deemed the decision of the panel for all purposes hereof. If two or more members of the arbitration panel cannot agree, then the decision of the arbitrator not appointed by any Member shall control. The references herein to the arbitration panel shall also be deemed to refer to a single arbitrator where a panel is not being used hereunder, and all references to decisions, orders, awards and relief granted by the panel of arbitrators shall mean the decision, order, award or relief agreed upon in writing by the required number of members of the panel, as indicated.
(v) The Members agree that the arbitration panel may render and the Members shall abide by any interim ruling that the arbitration panel deems necessary or prudent regarding discovery, summary proceedings, or other pre-arbitration matters.
(vi) The Members hereby submit to the in personam jurisdiction of the state and federal courts located in Texas, and agree that any such court may enter all such orders as may be necessary or appropriate to enforce and/or to confirm any ruling or decision or any award rendered by the arbitration panel. Any court of law of Texas or the United States of America shall enforce the decision of the panel of arbitrators (or single arbitrator, as applicable) in its entirety and only in its entirety; provided, however, that if a court for any reason refuses to enforce any equitable remedies ordered by the arbitration panel, such refusal shall not affect any damage or attorney fee award made by the arbitration panel.
(vii) Each Member shall bear its own costs or other expenses, including reasonable attorneys??? fees and costs incurred by such Member, arising out of or occurring because of the arbitration proceedings. Each Member involved in the Dispute shall each pay the fees, costs and expenses charged by the arbitrator chosen by it, and, in advance, its equal share of the fees, costs and expenses charged by the third arbitrator; provided, however, that in the event that there is a single arbitrator, the fees and expenses of such arbitrator shall be borne equally between the Members involved in the Dispute.
(viii) Third parties dealing with any Member shall be entitled to fully rely on any written arbitration order or decision with regard to the matters addressed therein, whether or not such arbitration order or decision has been confirmed or adopted by a court, or incorporated in any order of any court.
