2.1 Engagement of the Common Facilities Manager. The Co-Owners hereby engage the Common Facilities Manager as an independent contractor to manage, operate, maintain and repair the Common Facilities and to perform other duties pertaining to the Shared Assets, all as set forth in this Agreement. The Common Facilities Manager accepts such engagement and agrees to perform such duties in accordance with the terms and conditions hereof. In accordance with Section 4.6, Flat Ridge 2 hereby engages the Common Facilities Manager as its Delegate (as defined in the Flat Ridge Interconnection LLCA) to perform the duties of Manager under the Flat Ridge Interconnection LLCA.
2.2 Relationship. The Common Facilities Manager shall act as an independent contractor of the Co-Owners with respect to the performance of its obligations hereunder. Neither the Common Facilities Manager nor any of its Affiliates, employees, subcontractors, vendors or suppliers, or any employees of any of the foregoing Persons shall be deemed to be agents, representatives, employees, or servants of the Co-Owners as a result of this Agreement or of performing any duties hereunder, and no such Person as a result of entering into this Agreement or of performing any duties hereunder shall have the right, authority, obligation or duty to assume, create or incur any liability or obligation, express or implied, against, in the name of, or on behalf of the Co-Owners, except that the Common Facilities Manager has the right and obligation to act for and on behalf of and to bind the Co-Owners to the extent expressly contemplated by and in accordance with this Agreement. In no case shall this Agreement be construed to create a relationship of partnership or any other association of profit between or among or between any of the Co-Owners, on the one hand, and the Common Facilities Manager
or any of its Affiliates, employees, subcontractors, vendors or suppliers, or any employees of any of the foregoing Persons, on the other hand.
2.3 Engagement of Third Parties. The Common Facilities Manager may engage such Persons (including the Common Facilities Manager???s Affiliates) as it deems advisable for the purpose of performing or carrying out any of its obligations under this Agreement (such Persons, the ???Subcontractors???); provided, however, that (i) no such engagement shall relieve the Common Facilities Manager of any of its obligations or liabilities under this Agreement, including those set forth in Article 11, and (ii) the engagement of any proposed Subcontractor is subject to Co-Owner Approval, not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed, if the annual amount payable to such Subcontractor (or any Affiliate of such Subcontractor) under the relevant subcontract or subcontracts exceeds one hundred thousand dollars ($100,000.00). In no case shall any of the Co-Owners be deemed to have contractual privity with any Subcontractor solely as a result of the engagement by the Common Facilities Manager of such Subcontractor for the provision of Services.
2.4 Representatives.
(a) The Common Facilities Manager hereby designates Joseph Mills as its representative under this Agreement. Such representative is authorized to grant or deny approvals or consents and take such other action on behalf of the Common Facilities Manager required under this Agreement; provided that such representative shall not have the power to amend or waive any provision of this Agreement. The representative shall have the authority to bind the Common Facilities Manager until such time as the Common Facilities Manager delivers written notice in accordance with the terms hereof rescinding the authority of such representative, in which event the Common Facilities Manager shall designate a replacement representative with binding authority under this Agreement. In addition, each Party shall, at its sole expense, dedicate sufficient and qualified personnel to the Common Facilities so that decisions and required approvals can be made in a timely and expeditious manner.
(b) The Common Facilities Manager shall designate an individual as its manager of the Shared Assets (the ???Site Manager???) under this Agreement within thirty (30) Days after the Commencement Date. The Site Manager shall oversee, on behalf of Common Facilities Manager, the performance of the Services (and Additional Services, as applicable) in respect of the Shared Assets. The Common Facilities Manager shall not designate or substitute the Site Manager with any other person without unanimous Co-Owner Approval (such approval not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed). The Co-Owners shall, in their reasonable discretion, in compliance with all applicable Laws and acting unanimously, have the right to direct Common Facilities Manager to remove the Site Manager from the Project Site and to direct the Common Facilities Manager to appoint a different Site Manager to the Project Site. The Common Facilities Manager shall appoint such new Site Manager as soon as reasonably practicable, but in no event more than fifteen (15) Days following removal of the prior Site Manager or direction by the Co-Owners to appoint a new Site Manager, as applicable.
2.5 Flat Ridge Interconnection. As the Interconnection Customer under the Shared GIA, Flat Ridge Interconnection does not own a separate generating project and does not have an ownership interest in any Common Facilities. Certain of the Co-Owners have received
interconnection rights through their ownership of Flat Ridge Interconnection as required in accordance with Section 7.2(b) of the Common Facilities Agreement. Flat Ridge Interconnection joins this Agreement for the limited purpose of allowing the Shared Facilities Manager to interact with the Interconnection Provider as may be necessary from time to time to fulfill its duties as Shared Facilities Manager.
ARTICLE 3 TERM
3.1 Term. The initial term of this Agreement shall commence on the date first set forth above (the ???Commencement Date???) and shall continue for five (5) years (the ???Initial Term???), subject to termination earlier as provided in this Agreement. Upon the expiration of the Initial Term, the term of this Agreement shall automatically be extended for successive three- year periods unless any Party provides each of the other Parties with a written notice of its election not to renew at least ninety (90) Days prior to the then scheduled expiration date (the Initial Term plus any such extension being the ???Term???).
ARTICLE 4 COMMON FACILITIES MANAGER???S SERVICES; DUTIES; OBLIGATIONS
The Common Facilities Manager shall provide (a) the services described in Sections 4.1 and 4.2 from and after the Commencement Date and during the Term and (b) the services described in Section 4.6 from and after the Commencement Date until the earlier of (i) the date on which Flat Ridge 2 ceases to be the Manager (as defined in the Flat Ridge Interconnection LLCA) and (ii) the date on which Flat Ridge 2, in writing, revokes its delegation to the Common Facilities Manager as described in Section 2.1. The services described in Sections 4.1, 4.2 and 4.6 are collectively referred to herein as the ???Services???.
4.1 Services. Subject to the approval requirements set forth in this Agreement and the limitations set forth in Section 4.2(c), Common Facilities Manager shall provide or cause to be provided the following services from and after the Commencement Date on behalf of the Co-Owners:
(a) Shared Assets Operation and Maintenance. Managing, supervising, operating, repairing and maintaining the Shared Assets in accordance with this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreements, other Project Agreements and the Metering Protocol employing Prudent Wind Industry Practices, including the day-to-day management of the Shared Assets. The Co-Owners shall provide an operating and maintenance building, or make available an existing building, on or near the Project Site in which Common Facilities Manager???s personnel may perform certain of their duties. Specifically, the Common Facilities Manager???s duties include the following:
(i) to negotiate, enter into, execute, acknowledge or amend agreements necessary for the use, repair, management, operation and maintenance of the Shared Assets (as permitted by this Agreement and in a manner consistent with the applicable Approved Shared Asset O&M Budget), and provided that (A) no such actions adversely affect the rights or privileges of the Co-Owners except with respect to incurring additional expenses for the
accounts of the Co-Owners and (B) the Common Facilities Manager shall provide each Co-Owner with copies of any material agreement promptly following execution thereof;
(ii) to cooperate as required with any protocols for calculating and reporting to the Interconnection Provider or the Transmission Operator the disaggregation of hourly electricity deliveries by Facility, in compliance with the Metering Protocol;
(iii) to pay and collect amounts due in connection with the Shared Assets, and to maintain one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Common Facilities Manager in connection with its duties hereunder shall be maintained;
(iv) to expend monies necessary for the management, operation, maintenance and repair of the Common Facilities (in accordance with the applicable Project Agreements and Approved Shared Assets O&M Budget);
(v) to commit to the expenditure of or spend up to and including five hundred thousand dollars ($500,000) for and on behalf of the Co-Owners to make or expedite repairs to the Common Facilities as required due to an emergency; provided, however, that the Common Facilities Manager gives concurrent notice by facsimile, email or other written form to the Co-Owners regarding the nature of the emergency and amount of the expenditure;
(vi) to manage compliance with any Financing Agreements or Project Agreements to the extent relating to the Shared Assets;
(vii) to manage compliance with the Co-Owners??? rights in the Shared Real Property Agreements, Shared Agreements or Shared Permits (to the extent relating to the Shared Assets), including making any payments required thereunder; provided, however, that the Common Facilities Manager shall have no right to amend such rights in the Shared Real Property Agreements, Shared Agreements or Shared Permits;
(viii) to initially verify and, if necessary, update, the MW electric delivery capacity of the Common Facilities;
(ix) to file real and personal property tax returns on behalf of the applicable Co-Owners in relation to any Shared Assets;
(x) to execute, acknowledge, and deliver any and all instruments and take such other steps as are reasonably necessary to effectuate the foregoing and as are consistent therewith; and
(xi) to promptly notify each Co-Owner of any notice (or any other information reasonably anticipated to affect other Co-Owners) received by Common Facilities Manager from any other Co-Owner.
(b) Shared Real Property. The Common Facilities Manager shall, with respect to the Shared Real Property and the Common Facilities located on the Shared Real Property, oversee all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other
matters or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to the use, operation or ownership of the Shared Real Property or the Common Facilities located on the Shared Real Property.
(c) Metering Arrangements. The metering arrangements agreed with the Interconnection Provider are set forth in each Interconnection Agreement, a copy of which each Co-Owner shall provide to the Common Facilities Manager, and a list of metering equipment is set forth in each Interconnection Agreement. Subject to the Metering Protocol, and subject to any agreements or other arrangements between the Co-Owners and any metering agent or scheduling service provider that have been provided to the Common Facilities Manager by a Co-Owner, the Common Facilities Manager shall send to the Interconnection Provider and any metering agent or scheduling service provider the meter data from the metering equipment located at the Point of Interconnection, as required by the Interconnection Agreements, together with an allocation of such meter data between or among the Facilities in accordance with the Metering Protocol, and send copies of such meter data and allocations to each Co-Owner, and the Common Facilities Manager shall send to the Interconnection Provider and each Co-Owner a corrected allocation between or among the Facilities as required by the Metering Protocol, based on the actual meter data collected by meters installed at the low-voltage side of each electric substation in the Project. The Common Facilities Manager shall notify every Co-Owner of any changes to the Metering Protocol applicable to any Shared Assets Group or Common Facilities Group.
(d) Testing and Correction of Meters. Unless a different procedure is dictated by the Metering Protocol, in which case the Metering Protocol shall control, the Common Facilities Manager shall perform the testing and correction services described in this Section 4.1(d). If any Co-Owner???s Electric Metering fails to register, or if any Co-Owner requests that the Common Facilities Manager test such Co-Owner???s Electric Metering, the Common Facilities Manager shall promptly conduct such testing and make correction for meter errors as follows:
(i) If testing shows that the measurement made by a Co-Owner???s Electric Metering is inaccurate by more than one percent (1.0%) from the measurement made by the standard meter used in the test, an adjustment shall be made correcting all measurements by the inaccurate or defective Co-Owner???s Electric Metering for both the amount of the inaccuracy and the period of the inaccuracy, in the manner set forth herein.
(ii) In the event that a Co-Owner???s Electric Metering is found to be defective or inaccurate, the Parties shall use the Co-Owner???s back-up metering, if installed, to determine the amount of such inaccuracy, provided, however, that the back-up metering is tested and found to be inaccurate by no more than one percent (1.0%) from the standard meter used in the test. If the back-up metering is also found to be inaccurate by more than one percent (1.0%) from the measurement made by the standard meter used in the test, the Common Facilities Manager shall estimate the amount of the necessary adjustment on the basis of deliveries of electricity from the applicable Facility during periods of similar operating conditions when the Co-Owner???s Electric Metering was registering accurately. The adjustment shall be made for the period during which inaccurate measurements were made.
(iii) In the event that the Co-Owners cannot agree on the actual period during which the inaccurate measurements were made, the period during which the measurements are to be adjusted shall be the shorter of (i) the last one-half of the period from the last previous test of the Co-Owner???s Electric Metering to the test that found the Co-Owner???s Electric Metering to be defective or inaccurate, or (ii) the one hundred eighty (180) Days immediately preceding the test that found the Co-Owner???s Electric Metering to be defective or inaccurate.
(iv) To the extent that the adjustment period covers a period of deliveries for which hourly deliveries of electricity for each Facility has been reported, the Common Facilities Manager shall use the corrected measurements as determined in accordance with this Section 4.1(d) to recompute such hourly deliveries for the period of the inaccuracy, and the Co-Owners shall take such further actions as are needed to assure that each Co-Owner receives the appropriate benefit or detriment of the difference between the originally-reported deliveries and the recomputed deliveries.
(e) Curtailment of Delivery. The Common Facilities Manager may, in accordance with the following provisions and in accordance with Prudent Wind Industry Practices, direct the Co-Owners to interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power (i) when necessary in order to maintain, repair, replace, remove, investigate, inspect or test any part of the Common Facilities; (ii) if the Common Facilities Manager determines, in its reasonable discretion, that interruption or reduction is necessary due to an existing or imminent emergency; or (iii) at the direction of the Interconnection Provider or the Transmission Operator. With respect to any interruption or reduction of deliveries of electrical power pursuant to clauses (i) or (ii) of the preceding sentence, the Common Facilities Manager shall limit the length of any such interruption or curtailment to that time strictly necessary to correct the problem. Any interruption or curtailment of the Shared Interconnection Facilities made pursuant to clause (i) of the preceding sentence shall not occur during the period of June 1 to September 15 without Co-Owner Approval; provided, however, that such maintenance may be scheduled during such period to the extent (i) required by or necessary to preserve any equipment warranties, or (ii) the failure to perform such maintenance is contrary to operation in accordance with Prudent Wind Industry Practices. Unless directed otherwise by the Interconnection Provider, or except as provided below, the Common Facilities Manager shall curtail each Co-Owner in proportion to its Pro Rata Share with respect to the affected Shared Assets Group. Each affected Co-Owner shall promptly effect such interruption in, or reduction of, delivery as the Common Facilities Manager shall direct pursuant to this Section 4.1(c) upon notice from the Common Facilities Manager, which notice shall be reasonable under the circumstances. In the event notice is impracticable or a Co-Owner fails to promptly comply therewith, the Common Facilities Manager may effect such interruption or reduction by direct action. Notwithstanding the foregoing, in the event the need for the interruption or reduction was requested by or can be attributed to a particular Co-Owner???s Facility or portions of its Facility, then the Common Facilities Manager shall, to the extent possible, limit such interruption or reduction to such Facility or such portions of the Facility, as the case may be.
(f) Disconnection of Common Facilities. The Common Facilities Manager shall have the power and authority, subject to Prudent Wind Industry Practices, to disconnect the Facility of a Co-Owner (a) in accordance with Section 10.2(b) of the Common Facilities Agreement upon a Co-Owner Event of Default for which all non-defaulting Co-Owners jointly
request disconnection of the Facility of a defaulting Co-Owner, (b) if the Common Facilities Manager determines, in its reasonable discretion, that disconnection is necessary in the event of an existing or imminent emergency, (c) in the event of a request under or a continuing violation of an Interconnection Agreement or Metering Protocol applicable to such Facility or of applicable electric reliability requirements if such continuing violation creates an ongoing risk of disconnection of the other Facilities by the Interconnection Provider, or (d) at the direction of the Interconnection Provider or the Transmission Operator. In the cases of (i) an Event of Default for which a proper notice and cure period have already been provided pursuant to Section 10.2(b) of the Common Facilities Agreement, (ii) a real or reasonably perceived emergency or (iii) as directed under clause (b) or (c) above, the Common Facilities Manager shall provide notice to the Co-Owner owning the Facility being disconnected concurrently with disconnecting its Facility or as soon thereafter as is reasonably practical.
(g) Personnel. Providing individuals at the Project Site as employees or Subcontractors of the Common Facilities Manager (the ???Common Facilities Manager Personnel???), who (as between Common Facilities Manager and the Co-Owners) are and shall remain under the exclusive control of the Common Facilities Manager, and not as employees or subcontractors of any of the Co-Owners, as necessary to enable the Common Facilities Manager to perform all of its obligations in accordance with this Agreement. Each such individual shall be dedicated on a full-time basis to the Project Site. The Co-Owners shall, in their reasonable discretion, in compliance with all applicable Laws and the Co-Owner Approval process, have the right to direct Common Facilities Manager to remove any employees or Subcontractors (or employees of a Subcontractor) from the Project Site. The Common Facilities Manager shall require its employees and Subcontractors to comply with the Occupational Safety and Health Act, and the applicable rules promulgated thereunder by the U.S. Department of Labor and all applicable Laws affecting job safety including Common Facilities Manager???s Health, Safety, Security, and Environmental (???HSSE???) Requirements set forth in Exhibit C.
(h) Procurement/Disposition of Equipment and Tools. Purchasing, renting or otherwise acquiring, on behalf of and for the account of the Co-Owners (or as a Reimbursable Expense to the extent permitted hereunder), such equipment, machinery, vehicles and tools necessary for the operation and routine maintenance of the Common Facilities (excluding Parts, which are described in Section (n)) but only in accordance with terms, timing and amounts set forth in the then current and applicable Approved Shared Assets O&M Budget or as otherwise instructed through Co-Owner Approval. Using commercially reasonable efforts to sell or otherwise dispose of such items of equipment, machinery, vehicles and tools that are in Common Facilities Manager???s reasonable judgment worn out, obsolete, surplus or no longer useful for the proper operation and routine maintenance of the Common Facilities, each such sale or disposal to be made ???as is,??? ???where is??? and without warranties, and providing the Co-Owners with all consideration received in respect thereof and an accounting thereof; provided, however, for any such items valued at more than ten thousand dollars ($10,000) at the time of sale or disposal, Common Facilities Manager will obtain the Co-Owner Approval.
(i) Consultation with Co-Owners. Consulting and cooperating with the Co-Owners and other personnel responsible for operating and maintaining the Project in relation to the provision of the Services, including the development of the Shared Assets O&M Budgets.
(j) Reporting; Notices; Records.
(i) Attending such regular monthly and/or quarterly meetings as the Co-Owners may reasonably request, including any special meetings called by the Co-Owners; provided, however, that the Common Facilities Manager receives at least seven (7) Days??? notice of such meetings, and such meetings either are held within forty (40) miles of the Project Site, or may be attended telephonically.
(ii) Promptly after receiving the same, providing to the Co-Owners written notice of any communications, orders or requirements of any Governmental Authority, the Interconnection Provider or the Transmission Operator affecting the Shared Assets.
(iii) Common Facilities Manager shall cooperate fully and provide such records and other information relating to the Shared Assets that may be requested by the Co-Owners in connection with (i) the filing of their tax returns, (ii) the maintenance and retention of their books and records, and (iii) any financial reporting or other disclosures that may be required, and (iv) any audit, litigation or other proceeding by any Governmental Authority, including those that pertain to taxes.
(iv) Collecting and providing any information, to the extent such information is in Common Facilities Manager???s possession or is reasonably available to Common Facilities Manager, regarding the Shared Assets required for any reports to any Governmental Authorities.
(v) Reporting promptly (and in any event within eight (8) hours of becoming aware of an incident) to the Co-Owners and to any other Persons entitled to receive such notice any incident of explosion, fire, storm, or other emergency on the Project Site which could reasonably be expected to threaten life or property.
(vi) Providing prompt written notice to the Co-Owners, all in commercially reasonable detail upon learning of the event requiring notice, of (x) any actual or potential violation of any applicable Law, including a requirement of any Permit, (y) all events, occurrences, conditions, and issues that the Common Facilities Manager reasonably considers are material to, or are reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect on, the repair, management, operation and maintenance, or results of operations of the Shared Assets, including notices of Liens and claims of Liens and any and all notices under any Project Agreements of defaults, events or other conditions required to be reported to the counterparties thereunder, and including any violation of a Shared Real Property right and (z) any breach under any Project Agreement by any party thereto, and any claims or assertions with respect to any of the foregoing.
(vii) Providing such other reports and information as may be reasonably requested by the Co-Owners under the terms of this Agreement.
(viii) Preparing and maintaining an operations log in sufficient detail to document claims, if any, under availability or performance guaranties in the Project Agreements in respect of the Shared Assets.
(ix) Maintaining appropriate records with respect to the Shared Assets in accordance with the more stringent of the Prudent Wind Industry Practices and Contractor???s own record retention policies; provided, however, that such records shall be maintained, at a minimum, for the period necessary to enforce the audit rights provided under Section 4.2(a).
(k) Warranties; Damage Remediation. Managing, supervising and verifying that all Persons providing warranties for the Common Facilities comply promptly and diligently with all of their respective warranty obligations, and providing such Persons timely notice of all matters affecting their respective warranty obligations. Coordinating and scheduling the provision of all warranty work and cooperating with the Person providing such work. Assisting and supporting the plan and the implementation of remedial activities associated with any accidents or damage relating to the Shared Assets. In connection with the acquisition or procurement of materials and services for operation and maintenance of the Shared Assets, Common Facilities Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to obtain the agreement of subcontractors that all warranties applicable to such goods and services will be separately assignable to the applicable Co-Owners. To the extent that such warranties are not so assignable, Common Facilities Manager will notify the applicable Co-Owners of such fact and will thereafter cooperate with such Co-Owners (for the duration of such warranty) so that such Co-Owners receives the benefit thereof to the extent legally permissible; provided, however, that nothing provided herein shall preclude the Co-Owners from seeking to obtain or obtaining such warranties directly.
(l) Environmental, Health and Safety Plan; Security Plan. Implementing and prosecuting the written environmental, health and safety plan covering all operations with respect to the Shared Assets. Upon obtaining actual knowledge thereof, the Common Facilities Manager shall promptly notify the Co-Owners in writing of any of the following matters, to the extent related to the Shared Assets or the operation and maintenance thereof: any inspection by Governmental Authorities; any pending administrative or judicial proceeding; any material release of Hazardous Materials; or any health, safety or security incidents. To the extent the Common Facilities Manager becomes aware of any environmental, health, safety or security matter with respect to the Shared Assets that requires or is likely to require a corrective action, the Common Facilities Manager shall, in consultation with the Co-Owners and at the Co-Owners??? expense, undertake and complete such corrective action. Implementing and prosecuting the written security plan for the Shared Assets and investigating all accidents or damage relating to the Shared Assets in accordance with the applicable environmental, health and safety plan.
(m) Compliance with Law; Permits. Subject to Article 5:
(i) Cause the Shared Assets to comply with all Laws applicable to the repair, management, operation and maintenance of the Shared Assets, including those relating to occupational safety and health or environmental protection, and taking such action as may be necessary to comply in a timely manner with any valid orders or requirements of any Governmental Authority affecting the Shared Assets; provided, however, that unless action is imminently required, Common Facilities Manager will provide the Co-Owners with a reasonable period for response and discussion before any action is taken; and
(ii) Cause the Shared Assets to comply with any Permits relating to the Shared Assets, including making payments required thereunder; provided, however, that the Common Facilities Manager shall be required to obtain only the Permits required by applicable Law in connection with the performance of the Common Facilities Manager???s repair, management, operation and maintenance duties under this Agreement; and provided, further, that the Co-Owners shall be required to obtain any Permits required by applicable Law to construct and operate their respective Facilities and the Shared Assets.
(n) Parts. On behalf of the Co-Owners and in accordance with the applicable Approved Shared Assets O&M Budget, procuring all Parts authorized through Co-Owner Approval, and receiving, unloading, handling, storing and maintaining all Parts on the Project Site in accordance with the Parts manufacturers??? directions in such a manner as to comply with all warranty requirements. All Parts procured and utilized by the Common Facilities Manager for performance under this Agreement during the term of any equipment warranties shall be of specification and quality required so as to in no way invalidate such warranties, or any portion thereof.
(o) Force Majeure Administration. Promptly providing the Co-Owners with information regarding all Force Majeure claims or events relating to the Shared Assets, but in no event later than three (3) Business Days following the Common Facilities Manager becoming aware of the Force Majeure claim or event.
(p) Liens and Encumbrances. Keeping the Shared Assets free and clear of all Liens attributable to the Common Facilities Manager???s (or its Subcontractor???s) acts or omissions; provided, however, that this paragraph shall not prohibit the existence or recordation of Liens arising out of a failure of the Co-Owners to meet their respective payment obligations hereunder to the Common Facilities Manager or any other Person providing labor or services relating to the Common Facilities under contract to the Co-Owners.
(q) Permits. Obtaining and maintaining any Permit required by applicable Law in connection with the operations and maintenance of the Shared Assets and complying with any such Permit.
(r) Interface. At the request of any of the Co-Owners, provide such Co-Owner reasonable assistance in dealings with any independent system operator or regional transmission organization, Governmental Authority and other third parties. The Parties agree that the Common Facilities Manager is not an agent of any Co-Owner, and the Common Facilities Manager agrees that it has no authority to commit any Co-Owner, nor shall it purport to commit any Co-Owner, to any contractual obligation without the prior written consent of such Co-Owner.
(s) Consultants. At the Co-Owners??? request, obtaining and assisting legal counsel, engineers and other professional consultants in connection with the Shared Assets, it being understood that the terms of engagement in each such case, including scope, hourly rates, costs and expenses and expected aggregate of all costs, shall be subject to prior written approval of the Co-Owners making such request.
(t) Security. Maintaining security of the Common Facilities and the Shared Real Property consistent with Prudent Wind Industry Practices.
4.2 Other General Duties. In addition to the services set forth above in Section 4.1, the Common Facilities Manager shall provide the following services from and after the Commencement Date:
(a) Co-Owner Access; Audit Rights. The Common Facilities Manager shall allow the Co-Owners and their Representatives reasonable access to the Shared Assets for the purposes of:
(i) Inspecting the books and records maintained by the Common Facilities Manager with respect to the Shared Assets (excluding, however, (i) the Common Facilities Manager???s company books and records that do not pertain directly to charges or costs upon which Reimbursable Expenses are based, (ii) personnel information or compensation or benefits information pertaining to employees of Common Facilities Manager or its Affiliates (not based at the Project Site), and (iii) information covered by legal privilege or which cannot be disclosed without violating applicable Law) and the Co-Owners??? audit thereof (to be conducted at the Co-Owners??? sole cost and expense); provided, however, that the Co-Owners shall only have the right to inspect and audit such books and records for any period that is within the seven (7) calendar years from the date of final payment hereunder or the final settlement or disposition of any claim made pursuant to this Agreement. If any such inspection or audit discloses an error and that, as a result thereof, any overpayment or any underpayment has occurred, the amount thereof shall be paid within thirty (30) Days after receipt of an invoice (with reasonable supporting detail) with interest at the Late Payment Rate (except that any underpayment caused by the actions or inactions of Common Facilities Manager shall not bear interest) to the Party to whom it is owed by the other Parties; provided, however, that a Party shall only be liable for any amounts hereunder that relate to errors discovered and disclosed within the inspection and audit period provided for in this provision.
(ii) Maintaining any of the Shared Assets, to the extent such maintenance is not performed by the Common Facilities Manager in accordance with this Agreement or in the event of an emergency and the failure or unavailability of the Common Facilities Manager or its Representatives to respond timely to such emergency.
(iii) Notwithstanding the foregoing, when accessing the Shared Assets, any Co-Owner or its Representatives shall follow all applicable written safety, security and site rules established by the Common Facilities Manager.
(b) Shared Assets O&M Budgets.
(i) Within ninety (90) Days after the Commencement Date and no later than September 1 of each calendar year during the Term, the Common Facilities Manager shall deliver to the Co-Owners a proposed budget for repair, management, operation and maintenance of the Shared Assets for the following calendar year, or the portions of the year remaining (each, a ???Shared Assets O&M Budget???), describing the scheduled work to be completed in the following three calendar years and the general operational plans for the Common Facilities
during such years, including responsibilities and emergency procedures and detailing the expected revenue and expenses for the following calendar year including explanations for any material differences to the base case at closing. The Common Facilities Manager shall deliver a separate Shared Assets O&M Budget for each Shared Assets Group and set forth the respective amounts allocated to the different Co-Owners in accordance with Exhibit D. When approved pursuant to subparagraph (ii) below, the Shared Assets O&M Budgets shall be the ???Approved Shared Assets O&M Budgets??? for such year.
(ii) The applicable Co-Owners shall have thirty (30) Days from receipt of a proposed Shared Assets O&M Budget either to approve same or to assist the Common Facilities Manager in preparing an Approved Shared Assets O&M Budget by October 15th of each year. If a Shared Assets O&M Budget receives such Co-Owner Approval, such Shared Assets O&M Budget shall be the Approved Shared Assets O&M Budget for the following year. In the event that a proposed Shared Assets O&M Budget is not approved within the time indicated, the applicable Approved Shared Assets O&M Budget for the previous year shall be utilized, with all amounts therein adjusted by a factor of one hundred percent (100%) of the percentage change in GDPIPD, until such time as the new proposed Shared Assets O&M Budget receives Co-Owner Approval).
(iii) If, during any calendar year the Common Facilities Manager believes that a variance (in excess of the permitted variances described in subsection (iv) below) is reasonably likely to occur between the actual expense of repairing, managing, operating and maintaining the Shared Assets and the budgeted expense for a particular material budget item, the Common Facilities Manager shall timely notify the applicable Co-Owners of such belief in writing and advise the applicable Co-Owners of the necessary revisions to the Approved Shared Assets O&M Budget and the reasons for those revisions. Upon applicable Co-Owner Approval, the applicable Co-Owners and the Common Facilities Manager shall proceed in good faith to revise the applicable Approved Shared Assets O&M Budget in such manner for the balance of the year.
(iv) The commercially reasonable and necessary costs and expenses incurred by the Common Facilities Manager that are within ten percent (10%) of any line item on an Approved Shared Assets O&M Budget and do not cause such overall Approved Shared Assets O&M Budget to be exceeded, and which are otherwise incurred in accordance with the most recent applicable Approved Shared Assets O&M Budget shall not require any additional approval of the Co-Owners.

ARTICLE 17 DISPUTE RESOLUTION
17.1 Applicability.
(a) Unless stated otherwise herein, all Disputes between the Co-Owners, on the one hand, and the Common Facilities Manager, on the other hand, shall be resolved in accordance with the dispute resolution procedures set forth in this Article 17. Any Dispute between or among the Co-Owners shall be resolved in accordance with Section 11.5 of the Common Facilities Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, (a) the Parties may at any time seek injunctive relief from a court of competent jurisdiction, and (b) nothing herein shall prevent a Party from defending or pursuing any claim in a court or other proceeding against a third party that has been initiated by such third party. In the event any Dispute involves common issues of fact, liability or responsibility with any dispute or controversy under this Agreement, the Common Facilities Agreement or the Flat Ridge Interconnection LLCA each of the Parties agrees, where reasonably justified, to join such Dispute with such other disputes and controversies to seek a common resolution of all such matters.
17.2 Negotiations by Senior Management.
(a) In the event of a Dispute between the Parties, the Parties will use all reasonable efforts to reach a satisfactory solution by referring the Dispute to senior management of each of the Parties.
(b) Senior management of the Parties will meet as soon as possible, on no less than seven (7) Days??? written notice, unless specifically agreed otherwise and shall negotiate in good faith. Senior management of the Parties shall examine any submissions by the Parties, and shall, if the Dispute cannot be resolved immediately, agree to convene for further negotiations aimed at resolving the Dispute.
(c) Should senior management of the Parties be unable to resolve the Dispute within thirty (30) Days after commencement of negotiation by such senior management, either Party may, by delivery of written notice to the other, submit the Dispute to binding arbitration in accordance with Section 17.3.
17.3 Binding Arbitration.
(a) If a Dispute remains unresolved after the discussions of senior management of the Parties in accordance with Section 17.2 hereof, or if one or both of the Parties fail to comply with any of the time periods set forth in Section 17.2(b) above, the Parties agree that upon prior written notice to the other Party, either Party may submit such Dispute to binding arbitration and that all such Disputes shall be finally settled by binding arbitration, pursuant to the rules of the American Arbitration Association (the ???AAA???), by (subject to the first clause of Section (b)) three (3) arbitrators who are to be appointed in accordance with the said rules and who, to the extent possible, shall have experience and expertise in the subject matter involved in the Dispute.
(b) Unless all Parties can agree in writing on a single arbitrator within ten (10) Days after the delivery of notice referred to in Section 17.2, then, within ten (10) Days thereafter, the Co-Owners, on the one hand (which shall be entitled to specify one arbitrator), and the Common Facilities Manager, on the other hand (which shall be entitled to specify one arbitrator), shall each notify the other in writing of the name of the independent arbitrator chosen by them to participate as a member of a three-member panel of arbitrators. If either the Co-Owners or the Common Facilities Manager fails to give the other timely notice of such appointment, then the Party who timely gave such notice shall be entitled to require that its arbitrator act as the sole arbitrator hereunder. If an arbitrator is timely appointed by each of the Parties, the two named arbitrators shall select the third member of the arbitration panel within ten (10) Days after they have both been appointed, and they shall promptly notify the Parties thereof. Each Party shall promptly notify the other Party and the Party-selected arbitrators in writing if the third arbitrator has any relationship to or affiliation with such Party (a ???Notice of Relationship???), in which event another arbitrator shall be selected within ten (10) Days after receipt of such Notice of Relationship by the Party-selected arbitrators. If the two initially appointed arbitrators cannot timely agree on a third arbitrator, then any Party may request that the AAA select the third arbitrator. The arbitrators, to the extent possible, shall have experience and expertise in the subject matter involved in the Dispute.
(c) The arbitration hearing shall be held at a site in Houston, Texas, to be agreed to by a majority of the arbitrators on thirty (30) Days??? written notice to the Parties. The arbitration proceedings shall be held in the English language.
(d) The arbitration hearing shall be concluded within one hundred twenty (120) Days after it is commenced unless otherwise ordered by a majority of the arbitrators on compelling grounds, and the award thereon or decision with respect thereto shall be made within ten (10) Days after the close of the submission of evidence; provided that failure by the arbitrators to conclude the arbitration hearing or make such award or decision within the foregoing deadlines shall not invalidate such arbitration hearing, award or decision. Arbitration demanded hereunder by any Party shall be final and binding on the Parties. The decision, arbitration order and relief agreed upon in writing by any two or more of the arbitrators (in the case of a three-member panel) shall be deemed the decision of the panel for all purposes hereof. If two or more members of the arbitration panel cannot agree, then the decision of the arbitrator not appointed by any Party shall control. The references herein to the arbitration panel shall also be deemed to refer to a single arbitrator where a panel is not being used hereunder, and all references to decisions, orders, awards and relief granted by the panel of arbitrators shall mean the decision, order, award or relief agreed upon in writing by the required number of members of the panel, as indicated.
(e) The Parties agree that the arbitration panel may render and the Parties shall abide by any interim ruling that the arbitration panel deems necessary or prudent regarding discovery, summary proceedings, or other pre-arbitration matters.
(f) The Parties hereby submit to the in personam jurisdiction of the state and federal courts located in Texas, and agree that any such court may enter all such orders as may be necessary or appropriate to enforce and/or to confirm any ruling or decision or any award rendered by the arbitration panel. Any court of law of Texas or the United States of America shall enforce the decision of the panel of arbitrators (or single arbitrator, as applicable) in its
entirety and only in its entirety; provided, however, that if a court for any reason refuses to enforce any equitable remedies ordered by the arbitration panel, such refusal shall not affect any damage or attorney fee award made by the arbitration panel.
(g) Each Party shall bear its own costs or other expenses, including reasonable attorneys??? fees and costs incurred by the successful Party, arising out of or occurring because of the arbitration proceedings. Each Party involved in the Dispute shall each pay the fees, costs and expenses charged by the arbitrator chosen by it, and, in advance, its equal share of the fees, costs and expenses charged by the third arbitrator; provided, however, that in the event that there is a single arbitrator, the fees and expenses of such arbitrator shall be borne equally among the Parties involved in the Dispute.
(h) Third parties dealing with any Party shall be entitled to fully rely on any written arbitration order or decision with regard to the matters addressed therein, whether or not such arbitration order or decision has been confirmed or adopted by a court, or incorporated in any order of any court.

EXHIBIT C
COMMON FACILITIES MANAGER HEALTH, SAFETY, SECURITY, AND ENVIRONMENTAL REQUIREMENTS
Common Facilities Manager shall maintain a written Health, Safety, Security, and Environmental (HSSE) policy that outlines the Requirements for Common Facilities Manager and any Subcontractors performing Services, consistent with the requirements set forth below (???HSSE Program???). The HSSE Program will be written to ensure compliance with all applicable federal, state/provincial, maritime, and local statutes, regulations, enforceable agreements, agency orders, permits, and Agreement documents. The HSSE Program will also include specific requirements of the Co-Owners and any site-specific requirements, including the Security Plan, the Safety Plan and the EMP. Common Facilities Manager shall ensure that any Subcontractor it employs complies with the HSSE Program. Common Facilities Manager shall take any additional precautions necessary to prevent harm to personnel or damage to the environment, property, or the Co-Owners??? reputation.
The wellbeing of employees, visitors and the community is of the highest importance to the Co-Owners. The Co-Owners are strongly committed to creating a culture of safety and compliance that integrates itself into all activities at the site. Common Facilities Manager???s Program shall be designed to further this commitment and shall include an HSSE Program with a focus on continuous performance improvement. The Program shall be designed and administered to achieve a 12-month rolling Total Recordable Incident Rate (TRIR) equal to or better than the TRIR set by the Co-Owners for work conducted at the Common Facilities. The Co-Owners may revise the TRIR target downward annually to achieve the goal of an incident and injury free workplace. The Co-Owners will audit Common Facilities Manager???s HSSE Program and documents, including those of Subcontractors. At a minimum, the following elements shall be included in Common Facilities Manager???s HSSE Program:
A) Required Elements for Common Facilities Manager???s HSSE Program
1. Leadership Commitment. Common Facilities Manager???s leadership and management at all levels in the company are fully committed to make safety of employees, visitors, and the community the absolute top priority.
2. Employee involvement. All employees, regardless of position are required to be involved in the HSSE Program.
3. The Common Facilities Manager will develop a comprehensive written HSSE training program, which shall specifically include the training requirements set forth in the Environmental Health and Safety Plan, the Security Plan, and the Environmental Management Plan. All Common Facilities Manager???s employees and its Subcontractors??? employees will participate in the training program.
4. Common Facilities Manager shall have clearly defined HSSE requirements, including the processes for planning, tracking, and verifying compliance. Control of work processes, site boundaries, and authorities shall be clearly defined, agreed, and implemented.
5. Common Facilities Manager shall have a hazard identification and risk assessment process for completing a daily pre-job task hazard analysis and/or work permitting system to identify and control the hazards to an acceptable level.
6. All of Common Facilities Manager???s employees will be trained in the recognition and mitigation of hazards. Common Facilities Manager shall communicate to Common Facilities Manager???s employees the expectation that everyone has an obligation to stop work that is unsafe.
7. Common Facilities Manager shall have a behavior-based safety program which, at a minimum, shall include a safety observation program with performance targets. The program shall have elements for rewarding appropriate behavior and a progressive discipline policy to address inappropriate behavior.
8. Common Facilities Manager will have a written policy for reporting all safety, security and environmental incidents to the Co-Owners. Common Facilities Manager???s management will investigate all recordable incidents. Common Facilities Manager will investigate at its discretion, or at the request of the Co-Owners, safety violations and near misses that do not cause an injury. Each Owner will conduct a separate investigation at its discretion.
9. Common Facilities Manager shall ensure that regulatory required training for Common Facilities Manager???s employees has been identified and completed. Competency shall be demonstrated. The Co-Owners may require additional site-specific training and documentation.
10. Common Facilities Manager shall have a written Waste Management plan for use at the Common Facilities site for Services performed, which at a minimum, requires identification of waste and disposal methods.
11. Common Facilities Manager shall have an acceptable Common Facilities Manager Environmental Management System (EMS).
12. Common Facilities Manager shall comply with the Driving Standard as provided to Common Facilities Manager by the Co-Owners.
13. Common Facilities Manager shall have and apply a Fitness-for-Duty program which includes assessment of the physical capability of Common Facilities Manager???s employees to perform certain specific tasks and a physical agility testing component.
14. Common Facilities Manager shall have an up to date Environmental, Health and Safety Plan and an up to date Security Plan with historical records that provide assurance that the Environmental, Health and Safety Plan and the Security Plan are being faithfully executed and evidence the degree to which all of Common Facilities Manager???s employees have been trained and have demonstrated that they understand and have the knowledge to comply with the Environmental, Health and Safety Plan and the Security Plan.
15. Firearms and weapons are prohibited on all property owned, operated, leased by, or under the control of any Owner. Common Facilities Manager shall ensure its employees, Affiliates, sub-tiers, vendors or Subcontractors not possess or transport weapons or firearms onto such property.
B) HSSE Meetings
Common Facilities Manager shall conduct or take part in regularly scheduled on-site or off-site HSSE meetings discussing, among other topics, facility and job hazards, incidents, near-misses, site-specific safety and health rules, and site-specific procedures.
C) Incident Reporting and Investigations
Common Facilities Manager shall immediately notify each Owner of all Common Facilities Manager or Subcontractor incidents resulting in personal injury, spills or releases, security issues, loss or damage to property, or near-misses as well as incidents requiring notification under the Environmental Management Plan, and including any inspections by Governmental Authorities and any pending administrative or judicial proceeding. The Co-Owners (acting unanimously) may require Common Facilities Manager to conduct an investigation for any HSSE incident. Each Owner retains the right to participate or conduct its own incident investigation. For all incident investigations, Common Facilities Manager shall provide a written investigation report to each Owner. The investigation report shall identify possible root causes associated with the incident as well as proposals for corrective action. When requested, Common Facilities Manager shall furnish each Owner with a copy of non-privileged reports made by or on behalf of Common Facilities Manager concerning an incident, including any non- privileged statements or other investigative material.
D) Personal Protective Equipment
Common Facilities Manager shall ensure Common Facilities Manager???s employees have proper personal protective equipment (PPE) before Services begin, and that PPE is worn as required. Common Facilities Manager shall obtain and comply with individual site PPE requirements.
E) Common Facilities Manager???s Employee Conduct
Common Facilities Manager shall comply fully with the Substance Abuse Policy attached hereto.
Each Owner has the right to require Common Facilities Manager to remove and bar from the Project Site any personnel whose conduct (condition or action) jeopardizes the safety of any person. In addition, Common Facilities Manager shall not permit any barred person to work at any other of the Co-Owners??? sites, including sites of the Co-Owners??? affiliates, without prior written approval from the Co-Owners.
F) Common Facilities Manager???s Employee HSSE Competency
Common Facilities Manager shall ensure that regulatory required training for Common Facilities Manager???s employees has been identified and completed. Competency shall be demonstrated.
The Co-Owners (acting unanimously) may require additional site-specific training and documentation.
Common Facilities Manager shall have clearly defined HSSE requirements, including the processes for verifying compliance. Control of work processes, site boundaries, and authorities shall be clearly defined, agreed, and implemented.
G) Short Service Employee Policy
Common Facilities Manager shall comply with its own or the Co-Owners??? site-specific short service employee policy, whichever policy is more restrictive.
H) Preventative Maintenance Program
Common Facilities Manager shall have a preventative maintenance program that includes, at a minimum, the identification and prioritization of maintenance for safety and/or environmental critical items.
I) Chemicals Brought to Project Site
Common Facilities Manager shall ensure Safety Data Sheets (SDSs) are available at the Project Site for all chemicals Common Facilities Manager brings to the site, and that the SDS is reviewed as part of the JSA/JSEA discussion.
SUBSTANCE ABUSE POLICY
The Co-Owners have a strong commitment to provide a safe workplace for all persons working or visiting on its premises or for work being done on behalf of the Co-Owners. In order to assist in maintaining a safe working environment and to protect the Co-Owners??? property and assets, this Policy concerning substance abuse is established.
The Common Facilities Manager, its Subcontractors, and vendors who perform labor or services on the Co-Owners??? premises, for work being done on behalf of the Co-Owners, or on whose premises the Co-Owners??? employees spend substantial time, hereinafter referred to as ???Contractors,??? shall have and administer a formal substance abuse interdiction policy. Policies for Contractors and subcontractors shall include substance testing of Common Facilities Manager???s employees entering the Co-Owners??? premises or for work being done on behalf of the Co-Owners. For purposes of this Substance Abuse Policy, the term ???Company??? shall mean the Co-Owners and their respective Affiliates.
The failure of Common Facilities Manager to comply with the provisions of this policy constitutes cause for cancellation of the Agreement.
ARTICLE I - POLICY STATEMENT
1. The use, possession, concealment, transportation, promotion, manufacture, distribution, or sale of the following substances is strictly prohibited on Company
premises, including all property owned, operated, leased by, or under the control of Company.
2. No Contractors shall perform work for Company, report to work, be on the job, or be on Company premises under the influence of prohibited substances.
3. No Contractors shall test positive for the presence of prohibited substances in amounts exceeding the cut-off levels adapted by the Company.
4. No Contractors shall refuse to undergo a prohibited substance test required by this policy.
5. Prohibited substances are defined as: (a) any alcoholic beverage, the use of which is not authorized by the Company, (b) any substance that an individual may not manufacture, dispense, sell, possess, use, or distribute under the laws of the state in which the individual is employed or is working, and (c) any otherwise legal but illicitly-used substances. ???Otherwise legal but illicitly-used substances??? include (a) prescription drugs obtained without proper medical authorization, (b) prescribed drugs, over-the-counter drugs, and other substances not being used for their intended purposes or at intended dosage and (c) marijuana. Drug paraphernalia and similar items used for substance abuse are likewise prohibited from Company premises.
6. Contractors??? employee shall notify his supervisor when he/she is taking any prescription or non-prescription medicine or any other substance that he/she believes may impair his/her judgment or performance or otherwise adversely affect the normal functions of this/her mental faculties or physical abilities.
7. The Company reserves the right to report known illegal activity to law enforcement authorities.
8. Any contractor (or subcontractor, sub-tiers, etc.) meeting DOT requirements will be considered compliant with the Substance Abuse Policy. NOTE: This shall apply only to those contractors that fall within DOT testing requirements. If a portion of the Contractor???s or Subcontractor???s workforce is not subject to DOT drug & alcohol testing requirements and will be onsite or working on behalf of the Company, they must submit to a drug & alcohol testing program that is established by their employer for the purposes specified by the Company.
Contractors will submit a copy of their policy and program to Company employee designated to administer contracts or to a party as otherwise designated by Company. Such policy must provide for substance testing of employees and must meet the minimum standards as set forth in Article 2 below. Company reserves the right to deny entry to Company premises of any Contractor, subcontractor, or vendor who fails to present a written policy that meets Company???s minimum standards, or who fails to administer an acceptable policy.
A violation of this policy will subject the Contractor???s employee to denial of entry to Company premises and projects or perform work on behalf of the Company. Reinstatement of the access
privilege may be made after one year upon request of the employing contractor. Such requests will be evaluated on the merits of each case. A request will be granted only upon receipt of evidence that the employee has successfully passed a substance screen within thirty (30) days of the request and has successfully completed an assessment by a Substance Abuse Professional (???SAP???) and has complied with all recommended treatment or rehabilitation prescribed by the SAP.
ARTICLE II - TESTING
A. DEFINITIONS
For the purpose of this policy:
1. ???Substance testing??? means the analysis of urine, saliva, or breath; however, at times circumstances may warrant additional testing methods.
2. ???Chain of custody??? means the combination of procedures and documentation which provides a faithful and accurate written record of the custody of a biological specimen from time of initial collection of a specimen to final laboratory analysis.
3. ???Negative test result??? means a laboratory conclusion that the presence of a substance was not detected in a specimen at or above the screening and confirmation levels utilized.
4. ???Screened positive result??? means that an EMIT analysis has revealed one or more substances present at or above screening cut-off level.
5. ???Presumptive positive result??? means a laboratory conclusion that a specimen was found to contain the presence of a substance based on one or more analytical procedures which did include gas chromatography/mass spectrometry (GC/MS).
6. ???Confirmed positive result??? means a laboratory presumptive positive result that has been confirmed as a positive substance test by a Medical Review officer (MRO).
B. LABORATORY AND SAMPLING STANDARDS
1. Testing for the following substances, at the indicated screening and confirmation cutoffs, are recommended:
Drug EMIT Screen GC/MS Confirmation Levels Amphetamines 1000 ng 500 ng Cannabinoids 50 ng 15 ng Cocaine 300 ng 150 ng
Metabolites Opiates 2000 ng 2000 ng Phencyclidine 25 ng 25 ng Alcohol .02 BAC .02 BAC
Contractors subject to DOT testing shall abide by appropriate levels.
2. Specimens will be tested using an enzyme immunoassay (such as EMIT) and/or a radioimmunoassay (approved on-site testing is permissible). In this testing scheme, a positive finding is called a screened positive. All screened positives will be further tested using GC/MS. In this testing scheme, a positive finding is called a presumptive positive. All presumptive positives will undergo Company review.
3. Alcohol screening testing may include utilization of either breath or saliva testing. Tests which are screened positive will undergo confirmation via the use of an evidential-quality breathalyzer for confirmation of positive alcohol test results. Company review is not required for positive alcohol test results.
C. CONFIDENTIALITY
When Contractor conducts drug testing of Contractor???s employees for the purpose of establishing eligibility to enter Company premises or perform work on behalf of the company, such substance testing results which are positive will not be individually disclosed to Company. Contractor shall certify that each employee assigned to work on behalf of the company or on Company premises has passed a substance test that meets the standards of this policy. Contractor shall maintain records of drug substance which are subject to audit by Company (see Article 4 and Article 6).
The results of substance tests performed for reasonable suspicion or accident/incident investigations as outlined below shall be disclosed to local Company management upon request.
D. TESTING
1. Contractor shall conduct substance testing in these situations:
1. before Contractor???s employee may enter Company premises or perform work on behalf of the Company for the first time.
2. at least annually or a demonstrated random testing procedure and protocols for continuously employed workers who perform work on Company premises at any time or are doing work on behalf of the Company.
3. upon reasonable suspicion by the Contractor or Company that a Contractor???s employee on Company premises or doing work on behalf of the Company is under the influence of or has consumed any substance or item prohibited by this policy.
4. when designated by Company management, immediately following any incident which results in a recordable bodily injury as defined by OSHA, or damage to Company or Contractor-owned property. Additionally, any substance testing, following an incident requiring DOT substance testing as regulated and described by DOT (FHA, RSPA, and USCG), shall be strictly adhered to. (Note: Substance testing may also be required of the Contractor by Company following a near-miss incident. A near-miss incident is any incident which, if it had proceeded to a reasonably possible and more serious level of development, would have had the potential for personnel injuries, property damage, or serious liability claims).
5. unannounced testing of Contractor???s employees at a Work site of critical safety sensitive task or where there is reasonable suspicion of non- individualize prohibited substance use.
2. Contractor shall assume all costs associated with testing.
3. The refusal of Contractor???s employee to sign a consent form or submit to any testing will result in revocation of the person???s access privileges.
E. EXCEPTIONS
The following exceptions may be granted at the discretion of Company management:
1. Contractors hired on short notice may be permitted to begin Work on-site pending receipt of the results of pre-access substance testing. This permission shall not extend beyond seven (7) calendar days from the first date after Work starts by Contractor. Any person working under this provision shall be removed from the work site immediately upon receipt of a positive test result, or at the end of seven (7) calendar days if test results have not been reported. This provision is to allow Work to begin on emergency or short notice situations only. Testing shall be done as soon as reasonably feasible, and results shall be available within the seven (7) calendar days allotted. This provision covers only Contractor???s employees needed for initial staffing and does not extend to those hired with sufficient time for pre-access testing (2-3 days after job begins).
2. Contractors or vendors whose need for site access poses a minimal safety risk may be exempted from pre-access substance testing by authorized Company management.
F. VALIDITY PERIOD
1. A pre-access substance test shall have been administered within ninety (90) days immediately preceding access. This requirement may be waived by local authorized Company management for persons who are regaining access after an absence of not more than ninety (90) days.
2. Company will recognize a substance test conducted of a Contractor???s employee while that employee worked for a different employer provided that (1) the test is conducted within the 90-day period required by this policy, and (2) the laboratory and sampling procedures meet the standards set forth in this policy. Company requires that the testing requirements be verified by an independent agency, such as the Contractor???s Safety Council.
3. Continuously employed Contractors shall be substance tested at least once every twelve (12) months or through a documented random program with no more than six (6) hours??? notice prior to testing. Any of the various situations that require testing (pre-access, accident, etc.) will satisfy this requirement.
ARTICLE III - SEARCHES AND INSPECTIONS
Company reserves the right at all times on its premises to conduct unannounced substance screens, searches, and inspections of Contractor???s employees, vendors, and other persons, including their effects, lockers, baggage, desks, toolboxes, clothing, and vehicles. The purpose of such screens, searches, and inspections is to ensure compliance with this policy.
Any controlled substances or items prohibited by this policy, or any materials that are illegal to possess, will be retained by Company and may be destroyed or turned over to the appropriate law enforcement agency.
The refusal of Contractor???s employee to submit to a search or inspection will result in the revocation of the person???s access privileges.
ARTICLE IV - COMPLIANCE AUDITS
Company reserves the right to periodically audit Contractor???s records to verify compliance with this policy. Such verification shall include, but not be limited to:
1. examination of the Contractor???s substance abuse policy and its implementing directives and procedures;
2. a determination that substance testing is being conducted in those situations which require it and that the testing meets the standards of this policy;
3. examination of chain of custody procedures which ensure Integrity of collected specimens; or
4. evaluation of laboratory services.
Audit results will be treated as confidential so as to protect the privacy of tested persons. ARTICLE V - SUBCONTRACTS In all cases where Contractor is permitted to employ a subcontractor, the Contractor shall ensure that the subcontractor and subcontractor???s employees are in compliance with this policy.
Contractor???s subcontracts shall stipulate that Company reserves the right to audit subcontractor???s substance programs.
ARTICLE VI - CONSENT FORMS
Contractor shall obtain a signed consent demonstrating each Contractor???s employee???s agreement to release to Contractor and Company the results of any substance testing performed.
Company may look at substance test results at any time. ARTICLE VII - NOTICE Contractor shall ensure that each of Contractor???s employees and subcontractor employees is informed of the provisions of this policy and of the Contractor???s substance abuse policy. Notice shall include the consequences of failure to comply, and notice shall be made prior to entering Company premises.
ARTICLE VIII - CONCLUSION
Consideration for Work on Company premises will be conditioned upon Contractor???s implementation of a policy that, in Company???s sole judgment, conforms to the minimum standards expressed in this policy. Contractor shall develop and implement such a program.
The central goal of this policy is to provide a safe and efficient working environment for all persons on Company premises. Cooperation is vitally important to the achievement of this important goal.

THIS ASSIGNMENT AND ASSUMPTION AGREEMENT (this ???Agreement???) is made as of , 2020 (the ???Effective Date???) by and between Flat Ridge 2 Wind Energy LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (???Assignor???), and Flat Ridge Interconnection LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (???Assignee???). Assignor and Assignee are collectively referred to herein as the ???Parties???.
RECITALS
WHEREAS, Assignor owns, operates and maintains that certain wind power generation facility located in Barber, Harper, Kingman and Sumner Counties, Kansas with a nameplate capacity of 470.4 MW (the ???FR2 Project???).
WHEREAS, Flat Ridge 3 Wind Energy, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (???FR3???) is developing that certain wind power generation facility located in Harper and Kingman Counties, Kansas with a nameplate capacity of up to 128 MW (the ???FR3 Project???).
WHEREAS, Assignor is a party to that certain GEN-2010-005 Generator Interconnection Agreement among Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (formerly known as Westar Energy, Inc.), dated September 12, 2011, as amended effective July 25, 2012, as further amended effective March 28, 2018 (as so amended, the ???Shared GIA???).
WHEREAS, FR3 and Assignor intend to jointly utilize the interconnection rights granted under the Shared GIA in connection with the FR2 Project and the FR3 Project, respectively.
WHEREAS, Transmission Operator will not permit the partial assignment of the Shared GIA from Assignor to FR3, so Assignor and FR3 have formed Assignee, in which Assignor and FR3 each own a limited liability company interest, to be the single interconnection customer to hold such interconnection rights on behalf of the FR2 Project and the FR3 Project.
WHEREAS, Assignor desires to assign to Assignee, and Assignee desires to assume from Assignor, all of Assignor???s right, title and interest in, to and under the Shared GIA.
AGREEMENT
NOW, THEREFORE, pursuant and subject to the terms of this Agreement and in consideration of the mutual covenants set forth below and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, Assignor and Assignee agree as follows:
1. Effective as of the Effective Date, Assignor hereby assigns, conveys and transfers to Assignee all of Assignor???s right, title and interest in, to and under the Shared GIA, and the Assignee hereby assumes from the Assignor, and agrees to perform, all of the covenants and obligations of the Assignor under the Shared GIA, solely to the extent such covenants and obligations accrue from and after the Effective Date.
